---
import DocsLayout from "../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
---

<DocsLayout title="Workflow">
  <h1>Workflow</h1>
  <p class="docs-subtitle">
    The authoring loop: from blank canvas to exported runtime pack.
  </p>

  <h2>1. Start with a pack</h2>
  <p>
    Open the studio and choose an example pack from the sidebar, or start with
    the empty default pack. The <strong>Project</strong> tab lets you set the
    pack name, version, description, author, and tags.
  </p>

  <h2>2. Add assets</h2>
  <p>
    In the <strong>Assets</strong> tab, define each audio file your pack uses.
    Give each asset a unique ID, set the <code>src</code> path, choose a
    <code>kind</code> (loop, oneshot, stinger, ambient), and specify the
    duration. Optionally add BPM, key, and loop markers.
  </p>

  <h2>3. Create stems</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Stems</strong> are the playback wrappers around assets. A single
    asset might be referenced by multiple stems with different roles and gain
    settings. For example, the same loop might serve as a <code>base</code>
    stem at full volume and an <code>accent</code> stem at −6 dB.
  </p>

  <h2>4. Design scenes</h2>
  <p>
    Each <strong>Scene</strong> represents a musical state. Pick a category,
    add layers (each pointing to a stem), mark which layers are required, and
    set start modes. Define a <code>fallbackSceneId</code> for graceful
    degradation.
  </p>
  <p>
    A typical pack might have: Exploration, Tension, Combat, Boss, Victory,
    and Safe Zone scenes.
  </p>

  <h2>5. Map bindings</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Bindings</strong> connect runtime game state to scenes. Each
    binding has one or more conditions (field + operator + value) and a
    priority. When the game sends state updates, the binding engine evaluates
    all bindings highest-priority-first and activates the first matching scene.
  </p>
  <p>
    Example: <code>inCombat eq true</code> at priority 20 triggers the Combat
    scene, overriding the default Exploration binding at priority 0.
  </p>

  <h2>6. Define transitions</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Transitions</strong> control how one scene flows into another. You
    define the from/to scene pair and choose a mode: immediate, crossfade,
    bar-sync, stinger-then-switch, or cooldown-fade. Without an explicit
    transition rule, the engine uses an immediate hard cut.
  </p>

  <h2>7. Review</h2>
  <p>
    The <strong>Review</strong> tab runs automated validation on your pack.
    It checks for:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Unused assets, stems, or scenes</li>
    <li>Missing references (binding → non-existent scene, layer → non-existent stem)</li>
    <li>Duplicate IDs</li>
    <li>Missing required fields</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The review badge in the sidebar shows the total warning/error count at a
    glance.
  </p>

  <h2>8. Preview</h2>
  <p>
    The <strong>Preview</strong> tab simulates your pack at runtime. Two modes:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Manual</strong> — adjust state fields (mode, danger, inCombat, boss, etc.) with sliders and toggles, and watch the engine resolve bindings and determine scene/transition outcomes in real time.</li>
    <li><strong>Sequence</strong> — define a sequence of game-state snapshots and step through them. The trace table shows each step's resolved binding, active scene, transition, and active stems.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>9. Export</h2>
  <p>
    The <strong>Export</strong> tab converts your authoring pack into a
    <strong>RuntimeSoundtrackPack</strong> — a clean, game-ready JSON format
    with editor-only fields stripped.
  </p>
  <p>
    The export screen shows:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Readiness status</strong> — Ready, Warnings, or Blocked (if errors exist)</li>
    <li><strong>Round-trip verification</strong> — export → serialize → parse cycle confirms the output is parseable</li>
    <li><strong>Runtime summary</strong> — counts and categories at a glance</li>
    <li><strong>JSON preview</strong> — the full serialized output</li>
    <li><strong>Copy / Download</strong> — one-click actions to grab the runtime JSON</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>10. Integrate</h2>
  <p>
    Hand the exported <code>.json</code> file to your game engine. The
    runtime pack format is a plain JSON object with typed arrays — no
    proprietary binary formats, no vendor lock-in. Parse it with
    <code>@soundweave/runtime-pack</code> or with any JSON parser.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
